1. Initialize a 10-element array `count` to store the count of each digit.
2. Iterate through the string `s` from the second character to the last character (excluding the first character) and update the count of each digit based on its adjacent characters.
3. Iterate through the `count` array to find the maximum count and update `max_len` accordingly.
4. Return the maximum length of the longest semi-repetitive substring.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because it iterates through the string once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single array `count` with a fixed size of 10. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs simple operations and does not consume significant energy.

